  "text": "Given that TPPPs and MAPs are known to promote MT stability and post-translational modifications such as acetylation [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Tokési et al., 2010; [CITATION_3] , we hypothesized that Ringer and Futsch might also be involved in regulating acetylation and stability of MTs. Since acetylation of α-tubulin at lysine 40 is a post-translational modification [CITATION_4] ) that generally occurs on long-lived MTs, MT acetylation is viewed , futsch K68 /+ (E), futsch K68 /+; ringer/+ (F), ringer-/-(G), futsch K68/K68 (H), and futsch K68/K68 ; ringer-/-(I) labeled with Dlg (green) and Hrp (red). Quantification of fluorescence intensity ratio of Ringer/Hrp (J) and Futsch/Hrp (K) and total Type 1 boutons (L) in specified genotypes. n = 15 animals per genotype, Error bars represent mean ± SEM [ * p ≤ 0.05, * * p ≤ 0.01, * * * p < 0.001, not significant (ns)] (ANOVA). as a consequence of MT stability or age [CITATION_5] . We stained larvae of various genotypic combinations ( Figure 5 ) with Acetylated-Tub (Ac-Tub, green) and analyzed any changes with respect to total Tubulin (Tub, red). At the wild type NMJ, the AcTub signal is intense within the synaptic core and shows a tight fasciculation of the proximal NMJ branch and is much fainter in the distal/terminal boutons (Figures 5A,A ; [CITATION_6] . Single mutants of ringer (Figures 5B-B Figure 5G ). There were no significant differences in fluorescence intensity ratios of Ac-Tub/Tub between individual single mutants and double mutants of ringer and futsch (ns-no significant difference between mutants, Figure 5G ). We also analyzed the consequences of Ac-Tub localization and fluorescence levels following a presynaptic overexpression of full length Ringer and Futsch (using the Futsch[EP1419] line, [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] as seen in elav-Gal4;UAS-ringer (Figures 5E,E ,G) and elav-Gal4/futsch[EP1419] (Figures 5F,F ,G) . Although ratio of the levels of Ac-Tub/Tub in Ringer overexpression (Figures 5E,E ,G) seemed elevated, it did not reach statistical significance compared to wild type (Figures 5A,A ,G) . There was also no significant increase in ratio of levels of Ac-Tub in presynaptic Futsch overexpression (Figures 5F,F ,G) . The total Tubulin levels analyzed in all of the specified genotypes did not show any changes at the NMJ synapses (Supplementary Figure S2) . Together, these datasets revealed that individual and combined loss of Ringer and Futsch leads to significant decrease in Ac-Tub levels at the NMJ synapses.",
